      {
        "id": 3394102,
        "name": "Brad Baker",
        "username": "Brad_Baker",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/brad_baker/{size}/663_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-04-17T16:51:19.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Alan,</p>\n<p>Yes, a wine not talked about much.  Even though it is a single vineyard and first came out almost twenty years ago, it never really caught on or got much attention.  It stands out from the rest of the Taittinger range in terms of style, but not in a bad way.  It is just a wine very different from the rest of what Taittinger does.  Pierry as the village source and some large oak foudre use are the biggest differentiators.  Compared to the rest of the Taittinger range, I find the Folies to be fuller, rounder, and a bit more chewy, with a pear and peach leading profile.  I would never call this a knockout wine, but it is very good, very distinct, and a pretty good buy - especially in today\u2019s Champagne world.</p>",
